<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n40062a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40062a">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40062a"> 62(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> clich&eacute;s</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Arabic]</font> abounds in formulae such as repetitions of religious phrases which are unchangeable. There are certain stock comparisons, as Lokman&apos;s wisdom, Joseph&apos;s beauty, Jacob&apos;s grief, Job&apos;s patience, David&apos;s music, and Maryam the Virgin&apos;s chastity. The eyebrow is a N&uacute;n; the eye a S&aacute;d, the mouth a M&iacute;m &hellip; The cup-boy is a sun rising from the dark underworld &hellip; The cup-girl is a moon who rivals the sheen of the sun. <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE2"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 171</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Cf. <cite>FW</cite> 366.34-367.2 [a 1938 addition]. </mm> </dd></dl>
